text: People need to understand that it's actually Tom Cruise himself hanging from a FREAKING PLANE. It's not CGI, he does his own stunts and he's just hanging there with some safety cables.  Just like how he jumped out of the tallest building in the world in Dubai. I really appreciate when the action in a movie is as real as possible without a crazy amount of cuts, shakey cam and cgi to hide actors who can't do stunts and to hide the stuntmen.¬†  And also.. fuck yeah Ving Rhames is back!¬†  And also.. lol.. the Syndicate sounds like Hydra. ''Anti-IMF''.  PS: I really hate shakey cam. You can't even follow the action in most action movies nowadays. That's why I loved The Raid and The Raid 2. Full on action on screen in 1 shot with almost no cuts and no crazy shakey cam to hide stuntmen. Jackie Chan always did it best by doing his own stunts. Tom Cruise is far from an action star like Jackie Chan but I LOVE how he wants to do his own stunts. FREAKING HANGING FROM A FYLING PLANE!!!

text: OKAY! Let's write a constructive Youtube comment, to mix things up. All I see below is 'man, dat gai is crazy wit dem stunts' or 'i dont get all de Tom Cruise h8'. Screw that. Here's my call;  The M:I series is insanely schizophrenic. First movie was a very 60's-style suspense spy thriller with few explosions and more intense direction and ambitious cinematography. Second movie was your typical John Woo flick - violent, flashy, highly exciting but also DARK and EMOTIONAL, two other common John Woo traits that noone seems to talk about. Third movie mixed things up, it was more of a realistic, gritty and highly emotional action film with a bigger sense of desperation, and also a healthy dose of inspiration from the TV show 24 with Kiefer Sutherland. Great film. Fourth film? It seemed to be a throwback to the first one with it's retro kitsch and 60's-style spy shenanigans, but it was ultimately an action adventure a la Tintin, Indiana Jones or Modesty Blaise. I had a hard time taking it seriously.  What can we expect from the fifth one? I'm hoping it WON'T be like Ghost Protocol. I just watched M:I 4, 2 & 3 in that order, and it struck me how much more moving the 2nd and 3rd films are than Ghost Protocol. They're so very different from each other, but the films completely swallowed me whole, and I was in for the whole ride.
